      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

=E2=80=9CThe most entertaining outcome is the most likely,=E2=80=9D Elon Mu=
sk  once tweeted, as far as I can tell not about a particular event but as =
a general life philosophy. In that spirit, let me put out into the world th=
at the most entertaining outcome of Musk=E2=80=99s deal to buy Twitter Inc.=
 is obviously:
=09Having   agreed to close the deal by 5 p.m. this Friday, Musk in fact cl=
oses the deal by 5 p.m. this Friday, paying $54.20 per share to all of Twit=
ter=E2=80=99s shareholders and taking over the company.=09At 5:01, Joe Bide=
n calls Musk and says =E2=80=9CI am sorry, but we have decided that it is a=
 national security risk for you to own Twitter,=C2=A0you will have to dives=
t it immediately, this is an unreviewable and final order.=E2=80=9D=09Musk =
has to sell the company by noon on Monday, which he does at a fire-sale pri=
ce to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0its previous public shareholders? His lenders? Jeff Be=
zos? Mark Zuckerberg? Kanye West?   Jason Calacanis=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Crand=
os=E2=80=9D? Lots of good options here.=09He buys it for $54.20 per share t=
his week and sells it for like $15 per share next week, losing tens of bill=
ions of dollars.=09Probably he has a really intense weekend of messing arou=
nd with Twitter before letting it go? Again, many opportunities for antics.

This does not exactly hang together for a number of reasons, but would it b=
e funny? Yes. Is it the most likely outcome? No. Is it a=C2=A0possible=C2=
=A0outcome? Not really, no. But everything about this deal has skated prett=
y close to the edge of the possible, so who cares, I am typing it anyway, j=
ust in case.
On Point 1, it does seem like the deal will close this week. Bloomberg=E2=
=80=99s Paula Seligson, Katie Roof and Ed Hammond   reported last week:

Both sides=E2=80=99 bankers and lawyers are preparing paperwork for the buy=
out to be completed by the Oct. 28 court-issued deadline, the people said, =
asking not to be identified because the matter is private.=C2=A0
After months of public acrimony and accusations, talks between the two side=
s have turned cordial and are focused on closing the transaction rather tha=
n litigation, according to one of the people.
The Wall Street banks involved, led by Morgan Stanley, are also ironing out=
 the steps needed to finalize funding about $13 billion of debt commitments=
. One of the banks has told its staff to expect a borrowing notice from Mus=
k on Tuesday, said another person familiar with the matter. =E2=80=A6
It=E2=80=99s unclear what led to the breakthrough between Twitter and Musk.=
 In early October, their talks were stuck over Musk=E2=80=99s statement tha=
t his offer was contingent on receiving $13 billion in debt financing, even=
 though banks were already on the hook to provide the debt through a commit=
ment letter from April.
Another sticking point was that Musk had been seeking to reserve his rights=
 to file a fraud lawsuit over his claims the platform=E2=80=99s executives =
misled him and other investors about the number of spam and automated accou=
nts, Bloomberg News reported.

We   talked about this a few weeks ago: Twitter=E2=80=99s lawsuit to force =
Musk to close was barreling toward trial, even as they were also trying to =
negotiate a settlement where he closed the deal. But then the=C2=A0judge in=
 the case paused the trial and gave Musk until this Friday to close the dea=
l, which made everything much simpler. For one thing, the litigators who we=
re preparing for trial were sidelined, and the deal lawyers responsible for=
 things like writing the closing documents got to go back to work.=C2=A0Of =
course=C2=A0the talks turned more cordial.
For another thing, those sticking points don=E2=80=99t actually matter. =E2=
=80=9CShould closing be contingent on receiving the financing=E2=80=9D is a=
n interesting question if you are a Twitter lawyer fighting over whether or=
 not to=C2=A0pause the trial, but once the trial is paused and there=E2=80=
=99s a deadline for closing, the contingency is irrelevant: Either he gets =
funding and closes, or he doesn=E2=80=99t close (for financing reasons or o=
therwise) and you go back to court. =E2=80=9CShould he reserve his rights t=
o file a fraud lawsuit=E2=80=9D is also completely irrelevant to the closin=
g: He=E2=80=99ll close the deal by Friday, and then if he really wants to k=
eep suing Twitter=C2=A0he can.
  [1]

On Point 2, Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Jennifer Jacobs and Saleha Mohsin also   re=
ported last week:

Biden administration officials are discussing whether the US should subject=
 some of Elon Musk=E2=80=99s ventures to national security reviews, includi=
ng the deal for Twitter Inc. and SpaceX=E2=80=99s Starlink satellite networ=
k, according to people familiar with the matter. ...
US officials have grown uncomfortable over Musk=E2=80=99s recent threat to =
stop supplying the Starlink satellite service to Ukraine -- he said it had =
cost him $80 million so far -- and what they see as his increasingly Russia=
-friendly stance following a series of tweets that outlined peace proposals=
 favorable to President Vladimir Putin. They are also concerned by his plan=
s to buy Twitter with a group of foreign investors.
The discussions are still at an early stage, the people familiar said on co=
ndition of anonymity. Officials in the US government and intelligence commu=
nity are weighing what tools, if any, are available that would allow the fe=
deral government to review Musk=E2=80=99s ventures.=C2=A0
One possibility is through the law governing the Committee on Foreign Inves=
tment in the United States to review Musk=E2=80=99s deals and operations fo=
r national security risks, they said. =E2=80=A6
One element of the $44 billion Twitter deal that could trigger a CFIUS revi=
ew is the presence of foreign investors in Musk=E2=80=99s consortium. The g=
roup includes Prince Alwaleed bin Talal of Saudi Arabia, Binance Holdings L=
td. -- a digital-asset exchange founded and run by a Chinese native -- and =
Qatar=E2=80=99s sovereign wealth fund.
The panel operates behind closed doors and rarely confirms when it is condu=
cting reviews. CFIUS also holds the power to review deals that have already=
 been consummated.=C2=A0

Musk is a US citizen, so he is probably not subject to  CFIUS review,
  [2]
and kicking out his minority co-investors like Prince Alwaleed bin Talal or=
 Binance would not derail the deal. I do not=C2=A0think there=E2=80=99s muc=
h of a chance=C2=A0that any US government review will actually block the de=
al this week, or unwind it in the future. Oh sure I have joked=C2=A0about i=
t happening, and about it being Musk=E2=80=99s plan to get out of the deal;=
   I wrote:

The fancier=C2=A0possibility is that he is trying to=C2=A0get American gove=
rnment officials worried, so that they will step in to block the Twitter de=
al. =E2=80=9CWe can=E2=80=99t let Twitter, the =E2=80=98town square=E2=80=
=99 of American political discourse, be owned by a guy who might be a Chine=
se or Russian agent, so we have to block the deal,=E2=80=9D people think Mu=
sk thinks the government=C2=A0will think. By winkingly hinting=C2=A0that he=
 might be doing Vladimir Putin=E2=80=99s bidding, the theory goes, Musk wil=
l force the US government to=C2=A0block his acquisition of Twitter. Which w=
ould get him out of it, which is =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps =E2=80=94=C2=A0what=
 he wants.
I don=E2=80=99t really buy this =E2=80=94=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t think that t=
he US government has much of a mechanism to block the deal at this point, a=
nd I think it would be too controversial for anyone to touch =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it is a=C2=A0funny=C2=A0theory so I am passing it along.

Musk has also joked about it: Last week   someone tweeted =E2=80=9CIt would=
 be hysterical if the government stopped Elon from over paying for Twitter,=
=E2=80=9D with a crying-laughing emoji, and Musk replied with a 100 emoji a=
nd a crying-laughing emoji; there=E2=80=99s still like a 20% chance that th=
ose emojis will end up in a court filing. But I do think he=E2=80=99s kiddi=
ng. And if somehow this did happen (it won=E2=80=99t), a forced divestiture=
 next=C2=A0week is at least as likely (unlikely!) as blocking the deal this=
 week.
(Another very funny outcome, by the way, would be CFIUS rejecting the forei=
gn investors=E2=80=99 involvement in the deal,=C2=A0after the deal closes a=
nd they fund their commitments. If Binance buys Twitter stock from Elon Mus=
k at $54.20 this week, and a week later is ordered to divest it, does it ju=
st sell the stock back to Musk? What price does he pay? Like, 10 bucks, rig=
ht?)
I guess this thing is closing this week! It is a good thing I have booked a=
 lavish nonrefundable vacation to start Saturday morning.
  [3]
=C2=A0Part of me feels like I will miss this deal when it=E2=80=99s over: I=
 got to spend six months writing about remedies in merger agreements, a top=
ic that is both close to my heart and=C2=A0not in much demand=C2=A0except w=
hen Elon Musk is the one getting remedied.
But part of me feels like it will never=C2=A0really=C2=A0be over. Lots of s=
tory lines will continue past closing. Maybe CFIUS will make him divest. Ma=
ybe he=E2=80=99ll go around syndicating more of the equity to Calacanis=E2=
=80=99s randos.=C2=A0(At what price? If I were him, I=E2=80=99d go out at $=
69.42=C2=A0per share and see what happens; sure he=C2=A0thinks he=E2=80=99s=
 overpaying at $54.20, but what do they=C2=A0think?) And I am looking forwa=
rd to the initial public offering of Musk Twitter in a couple of years.
Also Musk Twitter is going to have to pay something like   $1.2 billion a y=
ear in interest to its banks, which will be hard, and should keep everyone =
on their toes. What if it doesn=E2=80=99t make enough money to cover the in=
terest? Will Musk chip in some money out of his own pocket? Will he not, an=
d dare Morgan Stanley et al. to try to take the company from him? What will=
 they do? Imagine being Morgan Stanley and deciding whether to foreclose on=
 Musk Twitter. The downsides of foreclosing are (1) Musk is the richest per=
son in the world and an important client and now you have enraged him and (=
2) now you own Twitter. Does not seem fun. Reasonably,=C2=A0the debt is sup=
er hung:

Banks that committed to help finance Elon Musk=E2=80=99s takeover of Twitte=
r Inc. plan to hold all $13 billion of debt backing the deal rather than sy=
ndicate it out, according to people familiar with the matter, in another bl=
ow to a market that serves as a crucial source of corporate funding.
The banks decided to park the debt on their balance sheets to avoid selling=
 it at a loss to bond and loan fund managers, who have grown increasingly s=
kittish amid rising market turmoil, the people said.
Twitter could have the dubious distinction of being the biggest so-called h=
ung deal of all time, surpassing a crop of them in the global financial cri=
sis, when banks were stuck with around $300 billion of committed debt they =
struggled to sell to investors.

There is something poetic about the world=E2=80=99s richest person issuing =
the world=E2=80=99s largest pile of unsellable debt. Most of the time, if y=
ou are a lender, you would rather lend to someone with a lot of money than =
to someone with less money. But at some point that relationship might rever=
se. Musk did not become the world=E2=80=99s richest person by being stable =
and conservative and always honoring the letter and spirit of his commitmen=
ts. Will he pay back this debt? Maybe! We have a few years to find out.
Also=C2=A0he=E2=80=99s going to  fire everyone:

Elon Musk told prospective investors in his deal to buy the company that he=
 planned to get rid of nearly 75 percent of Twitter=E2=80=99s 7,500 workers=
, whittling the company down to a skeleton staff of just over 2,000. =E2=80=
=A6
The impact of such layoffs would likely be immediately felt by millions of =
users, said Edwin Chen, a data scientist formerly in charge of Twitter=E2=
=80=99s spam and health metrics and now CEO of the content-moderation start=
-up Surge AI. He said that while he believed Twitter was overstaffed, the c=
uts Musk proposed were =E2=80=9Cunimaginable=E2=80=9D and would put Twitter=
=E2=80=99s users at risk of hacks and exposure to offensive material such a=
s child pornography.
=E2=80=9CIt would be a cascading effect,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cwhere y=
ou=E2=80=99d have services going down and the people remaining not having t=
he institutional knowledge to get them back up, and being completely demora=
lized and wanting to leave themselves.=E2=80=9D

As far as I can tell Musk=E2=80=99s basic content plans for Twitter are (1)=
 less moderation and (2)=C2=A0less spam, and while those goals do not logic=
ally conflict with=C2=A0each other, there is an obvious practical tension. =
Detecting and blocking violent, abusive, racist, anti-Semitic, etc. content=
 is not the same=C2=A0activity as detecting and blocking spam, but it does =
seem like they=E2=80=99d use overlapping skills and processes. If your phil=
osophical goal is to stop moderating content, then that works well with you=
r financial goal of firing everyone. But if you want to block spam, you nee=
d people to block the spam.
Also  there=E2=80=99s a near-term catalyst for firing everyone:

Some Twitter employees said they hoped to at least be employed through Nov.=
 1, when many are scheduled to receive their next equity grant and tranche =
of stock or cash compensation.
Other employees responded to the prospect of layoffs with dark humor, jokin=
g about how few people would be left working at the company after Mr. Musk =
took control.
=E2=80=9CPumped for our 2023 all hands,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0tweeted=C2=A0one Twit=
ter employee, referring to a companywide meeting. He included a video of ju=
st four people dancing.

So when I joked at the top of this column about Musk taking over Twitter on=
 Friday, gutting it over the weekend, and selling it on Monday, there was s=
ome truth to that. People who are still employed by next Tuesday get paid. =
Musk did not become the world=E2=80=99s richest person by always honoring t=
he letter and spirit of his commitments.
Also it is =E2=80=9Cnational emotional wellness month=E2=80=9D at Twitter, =
  oops.
Also   this is funny:

Billionaire Ken Griffin has committed to back Elon Musk=E2=80=99s bid to bu=
y Twitter Inc., according to a person familiar with the matter, though the =
amount he pledged was less than $20 million.
The backing from Griffin, who has an estimated net worth of $29.2 billion, =
hadn=E2=80=99t been disclosed publicly by Musk. Twitter had described the C=
itadel founder as an =E2=80=9Cactual or potential=E2=80=9D co-investor in t=
he equity financing for the deal.

I feel like =E2=80=9Csure, love it, I=E2=80=99ll kick in $20 million=E2=80=
=9D is more insulting than passing on the deal? That=E2=80=99s less than Ke=
n Griffin  spends on  real  estate in  an  average month.
  [4]


