   =20
      UBS v. UBS
   =20
 =20

If you are the chief executive officer of an investment bank, it is temptin=
g to think that  your bank is a tech company. =E2=80=9CWe provide technolog=
y tools to our clients to do stuff with money,=E2=80=9D is the basic pitch,=
 with the technology including both (1) financial technology (derivatives, =
structured notes, trade execution, funds, etc.) and (2) increasingly,=C2=A0=
computer technology (apps, smart routers, robo-advisers, a website where yo=
u can check your account balance, etc.). Becoming=C2=A0a tech company is a =
good development for a bank:
=09Doing tech stuff is less capital-intensive than doing traditional financ=
e stuff. Traditionally banks use their balance sheets to intermediate trade=
s=C2=A0between customers; writing a computer program to intermediate those =
trades uses less capital.=09Doing tech stuff is less=C2=A0people-intensive =
than doing traditional finance stuff. Banks are famously businesses where =
=E2=80=9Cthe assets walk out the door every evening,=E2=80=9D because the m=
ost important assets are the people, who have the market knowledge and clie=
nt relationships that make up the value of the bank.=C2=A0This gives them=
=C2=A0leverage to demand perks and bonuses and to jump ship to competitors.=
 Whereas if you build an app, it doesn=E2=80=99t walk out the door every ev=
ening. The market knowledge and client relationships live on your servers.=
=09Tech companies just seem like good businesses: It is easier to scale an =
app than a relationship business (you don=E2=80=99t have to hire and train =
thousands of copies of the app), it creates more stable revenue (the tradin=
g platform you offer to clients is less likely to lose a billion dollars on=
 a trade than your trading=C2=A0desk=C2=A0is), it gets valued more highly b=
y investors, etc.

Point 2 has a clear appeal to a bank=E2=80=99s=C2=A0CEO, but is less appeal=
ing to the people one or two levels beneath her. For a CEO, it is good to d=
epend less on the personal skills of temperamental senior bankers. For thos=
e senior bankers, it is bad.=C2=A0
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Marion Halftermeyer and Myriam Balezou report on confl=
ict between Ralph Hamers, the chief executive officer of UBS Group AG, who =
understandably wants UBS to be a tech company, and Iqbal Khan, the head of =
UBS=E2=80=99s wealth business, who understandably does not:

The Dutch-born CEO =E2=80=94 widely viewed as a surprise pick when he joine=
d two years ago =E2=80=94 wants to harness automated tools, streamline the =
byzantine executive ranks and improve the company=E2=80=99s standing in the=
 US, where UBS is eclipsed by local rivals. Meeting those goals requires th=
e embrace of lower-margin robo advice via algorithms and mobile apps, not a=
n easy ask of a breed of bankers accustomed to providing a personal touch. =
=E2=80=A6
But those attuned to Khan=E2=80=99s more traditional way of doing business =
are concerned about diluting a cherished brand built over 160 years around =
banking for the rich. =E2=80=A6
Ever the consummate networker, Khan likes to host gatherings at his lake-vi=
ew villa in Zurich, where he mingles with influential business leaders, cli=
ents and shareholders.=C2=A0
He makes regular use of the corporate jet to crisscross the globe and visit=
 customers. As Khan said at a conference last month, =E2=80=9Ceverything we=
 do starts with clients.=E2=80=9D But how exactly that connection is create=
d is where the fault line runs. On one trip to the US this month, Khan enco=
uraged employees in Los Angeles to build advisory relationships "not with m=
achines, but people," according to one person who attended the gathering.
Hamers, on the other hand, has said clients tell him that UBS has great pro=
ducts and the best advice, but that the bank must improve on its digital de=
livery.=C2=A0

The app doesn=E2=80=99t fly on the corporate jet, the app doesn=E2=80=99t h=
ost gatherings at a villa, the app doesn=E2=80=99t have the personal touch =
of a talented senior banker. But the app does scale, and the app is very un=
likely to cultivate support among UBS=E2=80=99s board and shareholders to t=
ry to win a power struggle with the CEO.=C2=A0

