<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">JPMorgan v. JPMorgan</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess I have a new goal as a writer, which i=
s that one day I want to be important enough=C2=A0that when my private bank=
er has a conflict with her bank, I can write a letter to the chief executiv=
e officer of the bank saying =E2=80=9Cback off my private banker, she=E2=80=
=99s great,=E2=80=9D and the CEO will make one of his main deputies write b=
ack to me with some bland soothing boilerplate, and then the whole thing ca=
n be written up in the press as, like, =E2=80=9CBig Bank Infighting Leads t=
o Stern Letter From Matt Levine.=E2=80=9D As I type this I realize that it =
is not so much my goal=C2=A0<em>as a writer</em>; it is more my goal=C2=A0<=
em>as a private banking client</em>. Specifically the goal is to become a p=
rivate banking client, and then to=C2=A0have enough money to (1) have a cel=
ebrity financial adviser and (2)=C2=A0write to the CEO and get a response. =
The stuff about the press is less important.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/29474809.275498/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvM2E0ZjM4=
MDgtMTlmYy00YTZlLTg1YjctZWEwZGYxOGYwNzli/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1b7c4110"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> Financial Times reports</a> that Malcolm Gladwell has made it:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Infighting at JPMorgan Chase over how to manag=
e the fortune of retired baseball star Alex Rodriguez has escalated into a =
two-year battle within the bank, involving prominent personalities such as =
pop sensation Jennifer Lopez and author Malcolm Gladwell, as well as chief =
executive Jamie Dimon. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the centre of the squabble is a prominent f=
inancial adviser named Gwen Campbell. She brought along clients including R=
odriguez when she joined JPMorgan from Bank of America=E2=80=99s Merrill Ly=
nch division in 2020 and set up shop at JPMorgan Advisors, as the old Bear =
operation is now known. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gladwell, a New York Times bestselling author =
of books including The Tipping Point and a longtime Campbell client, has ru=
shed to her defence, firing off a letter to Dimon on her behalf, according =
to messages seen by the Financial Times. Dimon has not responded directly, =
instead tasking other executives to reply to clients=E2=80=99 concerns.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI thought he was supposed to be a sta=
tesman, Jamie Dimon. This is like a game an 11-year-old would play,=E2=80=
=9D Gladwell told the FT.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CQuite apart from what he=E2=80=99s do=
ing to Gwen, I=E2=80=99m a client. My life savings are with JPMorgan. My fi=
nancial adviser has been exiled like Napoleon on Elba. Is that the way you =
treat your clients? I=E2=80=99m small-fry but a lot of her clients are not =
small-fry,=E2=80=9D he added.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He might be selling himself short there, bank-=
account-wise? We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/29474809.275498/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMTItMTQvc2VsbC15b3VyLWNvbXBhbnktdG8teW91ci1iYW5rZXJzP2NtcGlkPUJCRD=
EwMjQyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJ=
nV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAyNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBef67f2a0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  talked about the Campbell situation</a> before; tec=
hnically she is not a =E2=80=9Cprivate banker=E2=80=9D but a =E2=80=9Cfinan=
cial adviser,=E2=80=9D there are obvious overlaps between those roles, and =
at JPMorgan they seem to fight bitterly over client assets and credit. Part=
 of the problem here is that Rodriguez is (1) a longtime big client of Camp=
bell=E2=80=99s financial advisory business (including before she joined JPM=
organ), (2) a relatively small previous private-banking-type client of JPMo=
rgan, and also (3) a JPMorgan=C2=A0<em>investment banking=C2=A0</em>client,=
 as he is not just a rich guy but also an active businessman. If you want t=
o buy a sports=C2=A0team, that is both a personal indulgence (private banki=
ng and/or financial advisory) and a corporate takeover (investment banking)=
, and there will be some fighting over who leads the deal:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Before Campbell joined JPMorgan, its investmen=
t bankers had already advised Rodriguez and Lopez on a failed attempt to bu=
y the New York Mets baseball team in 2020. Rodriguez also kept a =E2=80=9Cl=
ow seven-figure amount=E2=80=9D at the private bank, Campbell claimed in le=
gal filings. As a result, when she joined, Rodriguez was designated as a sh=
ared client between JPMorgan Advisors and the private bank. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The private bank ended up winning more of Rodr=
iguez=E2=80=99s business by providing a loan for his acquisition of a minor=
ity stake in the Minnesota Timberwolves basketball team in 2021, Campbell a=
lleged in court filings. This was after Campbell was told that JPMorgan Adv=
isors would not finance the loan.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The article also points to a source of financi=
al conflict I had never really thought about, which is inheritance. I mean =
obviously I have thought about inheritance as a source of financial conflic=
t, but among the family. This story points to inheritance as a source of co=
nflict among financial advisers: If your uncle has a lot of money with one =
financial adviser, and then he dies and leaves you the money, and you have =
a different financial adviser, the financial advisers will fight over the m=
oney. =E2=80=9CThis money belongs to the heir now and I have a relationship=
 with the heir,=E2=80=9D your=C2=A0adviser will say. =E2=80=9CYes but I hav=
e a relationship with the money,=E2=80=9D your uncle=E2=80=99s adviser will=
 say.</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In another instance involving a different advi=
ser earlier this year, the private bank and JPMorgan Advisors battled over =
which division should manage money for a client who had inherited several h=
undred million dollars from a relative, according to a person familiar with=
 the matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dimon ended up intervening, telling both sides=
 that the bank did not have the market share for turf wars, the person said=
. It was left up to the client to decide which division they would park the=
ir money at.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gladwell is also selling Dimon short, statesma=
nship-wise. =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t have the market share for turf wars=
=E2=80=9D is a great line, and a=C2=A0good way to make both sides feel bad =
about the whole thing.</p>
